I don&#39;t have the capability of recording presently and haven&#39;t been involved
with MP3.&nbsp; But it sounds interesting so I would encourage any of our
group who does to participate in this with you.
&lt;p&gt;Regarding your rant:&nbsp; I have also read these tiresome posts on
&quot;up&quot; vs. &quot;ado&quot;, and they strike me as pointless as well.&nbsp; I tried
responding to this once, but it was futile.&nbsp; The people on the Shavian
site seem to welcome discussing this ad infinitum just as theologians in
the middle ages debated how many angels could stand on the head of a pin.&nbsp;
Perhaps, I&#39;m thick, but I really don&#39;t hear any significant difference
between what they insist are two separate two vowels.&nbsp; I pointed out
that the dictionary uses the same schwa symbol for all these words they
are giving as examples, but this does not interest them apparently.
&lt;p&gt;I do not understand your reference to the dictionary as I do not know
what the pronoun &quot;its&quot; referred to in &quot;as though no one could look up its
actual meaning.&quot;
&lt;p&gt;I also don&#39;t understand the comment &quot;I sound OK to me excuses...&quot;&nbsp;
My position is that most of us have no trouble understanding others speaking
English (unless it is a very obscure accent) and that there should be no
requirement that people spell words in QS according to some arbitrary authority
such as a dictionary as I do not believe the number of spellings that vary
would be so great as to impede understanding.
&lt;p&gt;I must admit I have seen QS and Shavian written with vowels that seem
very peculiar to me.&nbsp; In most instances, I assume this is from people
with little experience in QS or Shaivan, and they are inaccurately representing
their speech.&nbsp; Even so, this doesn&#39;t impede comprehension, it just
looks odd.
&lt;p&gt;Paige Gabhart
